  "prompt": "How do you file a complain against an online shopping website in consumer court?",
  "response": "Filing a complaint against an online shopping website in consumer court generally involves the following steps:\n\n1. **Gather Documentation:** Collect all relevant documents such as receipts, email correspondences, screenshots of the website, advertisements, and any other evidence that supports your claim.\n\n2. **Attempt Resolution:** Before filing a complaint, try to resolve the issue directly with the seller or website\u2019s customer service. Make sure to document all communications.\n\n3. **Draft a Complaint Letter:** Write a formal complaint letter detailing your issue. Include specifics such as transaction details, the nature of the problem, and the resolution you seek.\n\n4. **Locate the Appropriate Consumer Court:** Identify the consumer court within your jurisdiction. In many countries, consumer courts are divided into district, state, and national levels based on the monetary value of the claim.\n\n5. **Fill the Application Form:** Obtain the necessary complaint form from the consumer court. Fill it out accurately with all required information.\n\n6. **Attach Supporting Documents:** Attach copies of all your supporting documents along with the complaint form.\n\n7. **Pay the Required Fee:** There may be a nominal fee for filing a complaint. Verify the amount and make the payment as required.\n\n8. **Submit the Complaint:** Submit the completed complaint form, supporting documents, and proof of fee payment to the consumer court office either in person or via post, as per the court\u2019s procedure.\n\n9. **Follow Up:** After filing the complaint, keep track of its progress. The court might require you to attend a hearing or provide additional information.\n\n10. **Legal Assistance:** If needed, seek legal advice or representation, especially if the case is complex.\n\nFurther, the process may vary depending on your jurisdiction, so it is advisable to check specific procedures and requirements of the consumer court in your area.",
